{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17637239","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17637239"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:40:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:40:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17637"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17637","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17637"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10351"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75467"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10351","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10351"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17637"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60977"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4948"},{"type":"tags","id":"7747"},{"type":"tags","id":"7748"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24211"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24220"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75467","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75467"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA researcher is analysing data from a study measuring mean serum cholesterol levels in a sample of 100 adults. The sample mean is 5.2 mmol/L.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the relationship between point estimation and interval estimation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Interval estimation is only used when point estimation fails","Point estimates are always the midpoint of interval estimates","Point estimation provides more accurate results than interval estimation","Point estimation provides a single value while interval estimation provides a range of plausible values","Point and interval estimates measure different population parameters"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is that \u003Cstrong\u003Epoint estimation provides a single value while interval estimation provides a range of plausible values\u003C/strong\u003E. In this example, 5.2 mmol/L is the point estimate of the population mean cholesterol level, while a 95% confidence interval would provide a range of values within which we believe the true population mean lies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPoint estimation provides more accurate results than interval estimation\u003C/strong\u003E - Point estimates do not provide information about precision or uncertainty\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPoint and interval estimates measure different population parameters\u003C/strong\u003E - They measure the same parameter, just in different ways\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInterval estimation is only used when point estimation fails\u003C/strong\u003E - Both types of estimation are complementary and often used together\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPoint estimates are always the midpoint of interval estimates\u003C/strong\u003E - While this is often true for symmetric intervals, it is not always the case, especially with skewed distributions\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInterval estimation, typically through confidence intervals, provides important information about the precision of our estimates and the uncertainty in our measurements that point estimates alone cannot convey.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Point estimation provides a single value estimate of a population parameter while interval estimation provides a range of plausible values.","Confidence intervals are the most common form of interval estimation, providing a range within which the true population parameter likely falls.","Point estimates alone do not convey information about precision or uncertainty in the estimation."],"references":["Sullivan LM. Essentials of biostatistics in public health. 3rd ed. Burlington (MA): Jones \u0026 Bartlett Learning; 2018.","Dawson B, Trapp RG. Basic \u0026 clinical biostatistics. 4th ed. New York: McGraw-Hill; 2004."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60977"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17637"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60977","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60977"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-29T20:47:54+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-30T00:55:22+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10351"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75467"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"